# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] The **1921 Northern Ireland general election** was held on Tuesday, 24 May 1921.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] It was the first election to the Parliament of Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Ulster Unionist Party members won two-thirds of votes cast and more than three-quarters of the seats in the assembly.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Sinn Féin in particular was shocked at the scale of the Unionist victory, having spent considerable resources on the campaign, and had expected to win between 1/3 and 1/2 of the seats.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Sinn Féin and Nationalist Party candidates were successful in the joint County Tyrone/Fermanagh constituency with 54.71 percent of the vote.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] The election was conducted using the single transferable vote system.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] The election took place during the Irish War of Independence, on the same day as the election to the parliament of Southern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] As the election in Southern Ireland was merely a formality, with all candidates being returned unopposed (and therefore guaranteeing Sinn Féin complete dominance), Sinn Féin was able to focus its resources entirely on the election in Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] The Sinn Féin campaign focused on the issue of partition implemented by the Government of Ireland Act 1920, with Sinn Féin and the Nationalist party running on a combined anti-partition ticket.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Sinn Féin invested considerable resources in their campaign, placing advertisements in almost 50 northern newspapers making a range of arguments against partition.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Sinn Féin also published its own newspaper, *The Unionist*, of which 50,000 copies were sent to prominent Protestants in East Ulster, particularly County Antrim.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] In particular, Sinn Féin claimed there was widespread ignorance over the situation in Ulster and warned against the economic dangers of partition, particularly in relation to threats of a renewed boycott against northern goods in a manner similar to the "Belfast Boycott".
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Sinn Féin also attempted to attract Ulster's rural and agricultural workers, arguing partition would put them at the mercy of eastern Ulster's urban elites.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Despite the scale and organisation of the campaign, its arguments failed to resonate with voters, with the party's chief organiser Eamon Donnelly claiming on the day of the election that all Sinn Féin's efforts had achieved was assuring a high Unionist turnout.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Allegations were made claiming intimidation of Nationalist voters, arrests of candidates/organisers and the seizure of electoral literature.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Sinn Féin treated the two elections north and south as combined elections to the Second Dáil.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1921-northern-ireland-general-election] Five of the six successful Sinn Féin candidates in Northern Ireland were also elected for constituencies in Southern Ireland; Seán O'Mahony was the only Sinn Féin success solely elected in Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The **1922 United Kingdom general election in Northern Ireland** was held on 15 November 1922.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] There were ten constituencies, seven single-seat constituencies with elected by FPTP and three two-seat constituencies with MPs elected by bloc voting.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] Only two of the constituencies had contested elections.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] It was the first election held after the Government of Ireland Act 1920, which had reduced the number of seats in the House of Commons of the United Kingdom in the region designated as Northern Ireland from 30 to 13.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] It was also the first election held after the approval of the Anglo-Irish Treaty, whereby the Irish Free State separated from the United Kingdom with effect from 6 December 1922, a few weeks after the election was held.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The focus of politics in Northern Ireland had shifted to the Parliament of Northern Ireland, after the first general election to the House of Commons of Northern Ireland in May 1921.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The party leaders of the three parties had been elected to seats in this parliament rather than at Westminster.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] Voting only took place for 3 of 13 seats.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The other 10 MPs (all Ulster Unionists) were unopposed.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The Ulster Unionist Party was dominant in this election, and won the most seats at every election in Northern Ireland until the 2005 general election.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] They took the Conservative Party whip in the House of Commons.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The Nationalist Party was a successor to the Irish Parliamentary Party which had suffered a large defeat in the previous election, now continuing in the area of Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] In the previous election, Sinn Féin had won three of the seats in this region.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The Irish Free State had been in midst of the Irish Civil War from June 1922, which divided Sinn Féin into Pro-Treaty and Anti-Treaty factions (soon to become separate parties), and it did not contest this election to Westminster.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] In the election as a whole, the Conservatives led by Bonar Law won an absolute majority of 344 of the 615 seats.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1922-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The Sinn Féin members elected sat as TDs for the First Dáil, a revolutionary parliament for an Irish Republic.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The **1923 United Kingdom general election in Northern Ireland** was held on 6 December as part of the wider general election.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] Only three of the constituencies had contested elections.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] Voting only took place for 4 of 13 seats.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The other 9 MPs (all Ulster Unionists) were unopposed.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The election saw no change in the representation of the 13 seats in Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] In the election as a whole, the Conservative Party, now led by Stanley Baldwin, lost its majority and the Labour Party formed a minority with Ramsay MacDonald as Prime Minister.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1923-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The Ulster Unionists sat as members of the Conservative Party.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] The **1924 Northern Irish local elections** were held in January & June 1924 for the various county & district councils of Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] The election followed changes by the Unionist government, which had redrawn electoral districts, abolished PR for local elections, and implemented a requirement for members of local authorities to take an oath of allegiance.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] These changes are now widely considered by historians as gerrymandering intended to manipulate the election outcome in favour of the Ulster Unionists.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] As a result unionists won the majority of seats in several nationalist areas and most nationalists' victories from the 1920 Irish local elections were overturned.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] The elections were the first local elections to be held in Northern Ireland, which had been created by the Government of Ireland Act 1920.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] In contrast, Nationalists favoured the retention of a proportional representation based system as a safeguard for minorities.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] The Northern Irish parliament, dominated by the UUP who held 75% of the seats following the 1921 election, legislated for a return to the old FPTP system in 1922, and also legislated for the redrawing of electoral divisions.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] As a result of the nationalist boycott Unionists regained control of the county councils for Fermanagh and Tyrone, with no contests taking place in either county.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] In Belfast Unionists focused their campaigning on the wards most at risk of falling to the new Northern Irish Labour Party.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] Overall the results saw large defeats for Nationalists, Sinn Féin, and Labour candidates.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-northern-ireland-local-elections] After 1920 these parties had together controlled 24 of the 75 local authorities in Northern Ireland; by 1927 they controlled 12.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The **1924 United Kingdom general election in Northern Ireland** was held on 29 October as part of the wider general election in the United Kingdom.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The Nationalist Party did not contest this election.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] The nationalist interest was represented in the election by Sinn Féin, but they failed to win any seats, and the two seats which had been held by the Nationalist Party were won by the Ulster Unionists, so that all MPs in the region were from the same party.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] Three Ulster Unionists were elected unopposed.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1924-united-kingdom-general-election-in-northern-ireland] In the election as a whole, the Conservative Party, which included the Ulster Unionists, returned to government with 412 of the 615 seats, and Stanley Baldwin was re-appointed as Prime Minister.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] The **1925 Northern Ireland general election** was held on 3 April 1925.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] It was the second election to the Parliament of Northern Ireland.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] It saw significant losses for the Ulster Unionist Party, although they maintained their large majority.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] This was the last election for the Stormont parliament conducted using Single transferable voting, a form of Proportional Representation.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] Fifty-two members were elected in ten districts, which each elected between four and eight members.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] The Ulster Unionist government abolished proportional representation during this parliament and replaced it with the first-past-the-post system used in Great Britain.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1925-northern-ireland-general-election] In Down (eight seats) and Queen's University of Belfast (four seats), no actual polling took place as all candidates were elected unopposed: 10 Ulster Unionist, 1 Nationalist and 1 Republican.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] The **1929 Northern Ireland general election** was held on 22 May 1929.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] Like all previous elections to the Parliament of Northern Ireland, it produced a large majority for the Ulster Unionist Party.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] Though it had been argued this was done with the intent of gerrymandering, this has been considered unlikely as the Unionists already had a solid majority at the parliamentary level.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] However, the opposite was more accurate at local level.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] As with the rest of the United Kingdom, this has made it more difficult for independent and minor party candidates like the Northern Ireland Labour Party to win seats, as was the intent of the abolition of proportional representation was for the UUP to control the Unionist vote.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] 22 MPs (42%), mostly Ulster Unionists, were elected unopposed without any votes being cast.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] This began a trend which would continue for decades – until 1969, at least 20 MPs in every Northern Ireland general election would be elected unopposed.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] Only 30 of the 52 seats (58%) were actually contested.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] In 22 of the 52 seats (42%), only one candidate stood and they were elected unopposed without any votes cast.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1929-northern-ireland-general-election] The vast majority of the MPs elected without a contest were Ulster Unionists.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] A referendum was held in Northern Ireland on 22 May 1998 over whether there was support for the Good Friday Agreement.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The result was a majority (71.1%) in favour.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] A simultaneous referendum held in the Republic of Ireland produced an even larger majority (94.4%) in favour.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The total number of people who voted in both referendums was 2,499,078.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] All the main UK political parties (Labour, Conservative, and Liberal Democrat) supported the Yes campaign.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The only two parties in the Forum to campaign against the Agreement were the Democratic Unionist Party and the UK Unionist Party, though many prominent individuals in the Ulster Unionists also did so.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Some minor parties campaigned against it.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Republican Sinn Féin, which at the time did not run candidates in Northern Ireland, still opposes the agreement.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] In the Republic of Ireland, all parties represented in the Oireachtas were in favour – Fianna Fáil, Fine Gael, Labour, Progressive Democrats, Democratic Left, Green Party, Sinn Féin and the Socialist Party.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The referendum saw a large majority 'Yes' vote across the province on Friday 22 May 1998.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Turnout, at 81.1%, was very high for a developed country where voting is not compulsory.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] Turnout in the equivalent referendum in the Republic of Ireland was average for a constitutional referendum but returned almost universal approval (94.39%).
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The referendum in the Republic of Ireland was held on the same day but rather than explicitly seeking approval of the Agreement itself it sought endorsement of constitutional amendments required by the Agreement, and produced an overwhelming Yes vote in favour.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The turnout in Northern Ireland was noticeably high at 81.1% and also quite high evenly throughout Northern Ireland, compared to many elections where turnout is highest in strong nationalist areas and significantly lower in unionist areas.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] It is estimated that approximately 147,000 people who do not normally vote in elections turned out to vote in the referendum, most of them in traditionally staunch unionist areas.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] In the Republic the turnout was lower, at 56.3%.
[src:1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum/1998-northern-ireland-good-friday-agreement-referendum] The UK Parliament passed the Northern Ireland Act 1998, while in the Republic the Nineteenth Amendment of the Constitution Act 1998 passed into law.
